import java.util.Random;

class Solution {

    private int m;
    private int n;
    private int totalCells;
    private int[] cells;
    private Random random;

    public Solution(int m, int n) {
        this.m = m;
        this.n = n;
        this.totalCells = m * n;
        this.cells = new int[m * n];
        for (int i = 0; i < m * n; i++) {
            cells[i] = i;
        }
        this.random = new Random();
    }

    public int[] flip() {
        int index = random.nextInt(totalCells);
        int[] result = new int[] {cells[index] / n, cells[index] % n};
        int lastIndex = --totalCells;
        int temp = cells[index];
        cells[index] = cells[lastIndex];
        cells[lastIndex] = temp;
        return result;
    }

    public void reset() {
        totalCells = m * n;
        for (int i = 0; i < m * n; i++) {
            cells[i] = i;
        }
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1) for flip, O(m*n) for reset
space complexity: O(m*n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses an array to keep track of the available cells. When `flip` is called, it randomly selects an index from the array, returns the corresponding cell coordinates, and then swaps the selected index with the last index in the array. The `reset` method simply resets the array to its initial state. This approach ensures that all available cells are equally likely to be selected and minimizes the number of calls to the random function.

